title: For Sale/Trade:  Comanche III - .357 Magnum Revolver
postcontent:
6-inch blued Llama Comanche III in 357 Magnum. Has factory walnut target grips with Llama medallions on the side. Ventilated rib barrel, adjustable rear sight, spur hammer, & extra wide trigger (chromed). 

These were made in Spain and designed to mechanically function just like a Smith & Wesson Combat Magnum (model 19). Has pinned barrel, and recessed cylinder.

I listed this the other day and had to change my ad. Here's why I'm selling so low now. I haven't shot the gun in months and this afternoon was cleaning it and dry firing and found out there is a major timing issue causing the cylinder to not turn all the way between fires. It had functioned well and never did this before in the past. I've been wondering if some of the heavy magnum loads caused it. I'm going to take it to Hyatt's gunsmith this weekend and see if it's something they can repair, or you can get it for $60 and see if it's something you can fix yourself. I did take the sideplate off and looked inside to see if anything looked out of place. Didn't touch any of the internals, but if you know a good gunsmith maybe they can have a better look at it.

It's still a hand gun so according to law you must have a North Carolina CCW license or a pistol purchase permit. No exceptions. We'll both sign a bill of sale of which I will provide. If there are any questions, contact me. 

If ad is up it means it's still for sale.

The Springfield Armory GI Micro Compact 1911 isn't actually a replica of the WWI and WWII pistols, as 1911 pistols this small weren't produced until late in the 1990's. However, the Micro Compact is an excellent carry pistol that also has a nostalgic feel to it.

The Micro Compact G.I. has a 3" barrel and a framer that's smaller than an Officer's size frame, giving it a weight of just 33 ounces, and making it ideal for carry.

The frame and slide are forged steel, and are parkerized. The 3" bull barrel is fully supported and ramped, and is also parkerized. Parkerizing gives the pistol a finish that's much tougher than anodizing.

The reddish-brown hardwood grips are stamped "U.S.", and contrast attractively with the black parkerized pistol.

The sights on the pistol are original G.I. style, with a low profile notched rear sight and low rounded front sight blade.

The grip safety is flat, just like the old G.I. 1911's, as is the trigger. Trigger pull on the Micro Compact G.I. is five to six pounds, which is a good pull weight for a carry pistol.

The Micro Compact G.I. 1911 is a pistol with a lot of character, and one that can fit in the palm of your hand. It comes with a lifetime warranty that's good even if you're not the original purchaser.

postcontent: Defense revolver, offers great concealability thanks to a very unusual profile. The flat cylinder grants maximum comfort. The new Chiappa Rhino has revolutionized the revolver with a patented design that tames the prehistoric characteristic that most revolvers possess. The new Chiappa Rhino barrel is aligned with the bottom most chamber which is the key component to Rhino's tame characteristics. The position of the barrel lowers the center of gravity and yields a centerline of the bore more in line with the shooter's arm allowing for the most natural "point ability" while engaging a target. This characteristic also drastically reduces both recoil and muzzle flip which insures subsequent shots to be on target faster than ever before. The reduction of the recoil allows for the use of ultra light alloys to be used in the construction of the Rhino minimizing any adverse effect. The flat sided cylinder design of the Rhino reduces the typical revolver profile allowing greater concealment. With choices from 2" to 6" barrel lengths and sight options, the Rhino is truly a multipurpose handgun capable of reliable defensive duty, scoring ten rings, and taking game. Featuring both double and single action characteristics, the single action is actuated by a hammer cocking device that engages the unexposed hammer to prepare to fire.
